Impact of University Majors on Employment of Recent Graduates

Sudip Das

2024-12-05

1. Introduction

As a graduate student in the United States, I have experienced firsthand how challenging it can be to secure a job in the current market. This struggle is shared by many students, who often feel uncertain about their prospects after graduation. While the economic conditions may fluctuate over time, examining data from recent graduates can provide valuable insights into employment trends and factors that have contributed to successful outcomes in the past. By understanding these patterns, current and future graduates can make more informed decisions about their career paths and expected earnings.

This project aims to answer several important research questions related to career outcomes, gender disparities, and economic trends among recent graduates. Specifically, the analysis aims to determine which majors offer the best prospects for employment and salary. This involves analyzing the average and median salaries across different majors, examining unemployment rates, and assessing the availability of full-time versus part-time positions. It also identifies whether certain departments, such as STEM, Arts, or Business, consistently provide better outcomes for graduates. Furthermore, it examines whether there is a relationship between median salary and unemployment rate.

Another focus of this project is to explore gender disparities in the US education system. It will examine not only the number of male and female graduates in each major but also their income levels after graduation, to determine whether gender plays a role in career outcomes. Additionally, we aim to assess if gender influences the choice of specific majors, potentially impacting long-term economic prospects.

Overall, this analysis aims to provide a deeper understanding of the factors that influence graduates success in the job market and help prospective students make informed decisions about their education paths. By highlighting the relationship between field of study and employment security, the project hopes to shed light on which fields may offer greater stability and which graduates may be at higher risk of underemployment. Ultimately, the goal is to contribute to the ongoing discussion about the economic value of college degrees and provide meaningful insights for students, educators, and policymakers.

2. Related Work

Prior research, such as Carnevale et al.s report Whats It Worth?: The Economic Value of College Majors, offers a foundational framework for understanding the economic outcomes of various college majors. This report highlights disparities in employment and salary outcomes across disciplines, emphasizing the importance of examining major-specific trends. Link to article: http://cew.georgetown.edu/whatsitworth

This project is using data from recent graduates only. Similarly there is more work done and data collected for students currently attending university and women in STEM by the FiveThirtyEight site. Link to dataset: https://github.com/fivethirtyeight/data/tree/master/college-majors

3. Data

3.1 Dataset Overview

The dataset was collected from the American Community Survey (ACS) conducted between 2010 and 2012, specifically from the Public Use Microdata Series. This data is based on the outcomes of individuals who have recently graduated, offering a snapshot of employment and salary outcomes for graduates from different fields of study.

The dataset is part of the FiveThirtyEight site which is a popular interactive news and sports site started by Nate Silver. It is available on github and can be accessed through this link: https://github.com/fivethirtyeight/data/blob/master/college-majors/recent-grads.csv

The dataset includes key information such as:

  • College majors (computer engineering, finance etc)

  • Major categories (Engineering, Arts etc)

  • Total graduates (further separated into men and women)

  • Employment statistics (unemployment rate, full-time, part-time etc)

  • Earnings data (Median salary, percentiles)

  • Job type (low wage jobs, college jobs)

  • Rank (based on median earnings)

The college majors from the dataset along with their codes are categorized based on the information from Georgetown University Center on Education. More details can be found through this article: http://cew.georgetown.edu/whatsitworth

The data was collected as part of an observational study, rather than through an experiment, as it describes the real-world outcomes of graduates in the job market.

The dimensions are checked to be 173,21; which corresponds to 173 observations (rows) and 21 variables (columns). Here, each row represents an unique major, providing detailed information about the graduates within that field, such as their earnings, employment status, and gender distribution.

The numerical variables in the dataset are Total, Rank, Men, Women, ShareWomen, Sample_Size, Employed, Full_time, Part_time, Full_time_year_round, Unemployed, Unemployment_rate, Median, P25th, P75th, College_jobs, Non_college_jobs and Low_wage_jobs.

The categorical columns are major_code, major and major_category. Although major_code is represented by integers, it can be considered as a category as it represents the majors.

Out of the 21 variables, it would not be ideal to remove any columns, as each has its own significance and can be used in different parts of the analysis. However, some columns can be grouped or derived from others. For instance, the variables Major Code and Major both represent the same information but in different formats, which could be used together for reference. Similarly, the Total number of graduates can be derived by summing the Men and Women columns. These relationships between variables provide flexibility in our analysis, allowing us to examine both detailed and aggregated information to draw meaningful conclusions. Therefore all the columns would be used in this project.

First, a new column is added which represents the percentage of graduates in low wage jobs for every major. This is calculated by dividing the number of low wage graduates by the total employed graduates for that major. Second, the total sample size is calculated for every category. 5. Inference

5.1 Hypothesis Testing

5.1.1 Two-Sample t-Test on Earnings Based on Gender

Gender pay disparity is a common topic of study in labor economics. Here male-dominated majors are defined by majors where the percentage of male graduates is 60% or higher and vice versa for female-dominated majors.

# thresholds for gender
male_dominated_threshold <- 0.60
female_dominated_threshold <- 0.60

Research Question: Do male-dominated majors have significantly higher median earnings compared to female-dominated majors?

Null Hypothesis (H0): The mean of median earnings of male-dominated majors are equal to the mean of median earnings of female-dominated majors.

Alternative Hypothesis (H1): The mean of median earnings of male-dominated majors are higher than those of female-dominated majors.

Test Statistic: Since we would be comparing the means of two independent samples (male-dominated vs.female-dominated majors), we use the two-sample t-test. It is defined by the equation:

\[ t = \frac{\bar{x}_1 - \bar{x}_2}{\sqrt{\frac{s_1^2}{n_1} + \frac{s_2^2}{n_2}}} \]

Here x bar is the mean sample, s is the sample variance and n is the same size.

# Filter male-dominated and female-dominated majors
male_dominated <- indata %>% filter(ShareWomen < (1 - male_dominated_threshold))
female_dominated <- indata %>% filter(ShareWomen > female_dominated_threshold)

# Median earnings
male_medians <- male_dominated$Median
female_medians <- female_dominated$Median

# sample statistics
mean_male <- mean(male_medians, na.rm = TRUE)
mean_male
## [1] 49376.36
mean_female <- mean(female_medians, na.rm = TRUE)
mean_female
## [1] 33362.5
var_male <- var(male_medians, na.rm = TRUE)
var_male
## [1] 184286653
var_female <- var(female_medians, na.rm = TRUE)
var_female
## [1] 26821532
n_male <- length(male_medians)
n_female <- length(female_medians)

# t-statistic
t_statistic <- (mean_male - mean_female) / sqrt((var_male / n_male) + (var_female / n_female))
t_statistic
## [1] 8.299246
# degrees of freedom
df <- ((var_male / n_male + var_female / n_female)^2) /
      ((var_male / n_male)^2 / (n_male - 1) + (var_female / n_female)^2 / (n_female - 1))

# critical t-value for one-tailed test at alpha = 0.05
alpha <- 0.05
t_critical <- qt(1 - alpha, df)
t_critical
## [1] 1.668251
p_value <- pt(t_statistic, df, lower.tail = FALSE)
p_value
## [1] 3.836875e-12

This can also be done easily using the built in function

# Perform one-tailed two-sample t-test
t_test_result <- t.test(male_medians, female_medians, alternative = "greater", var.equal = FALSE)

t_test_result
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  male_medians and female_medians
## t = 8.2992, df = 66.054, p-value = 3.837e-12
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is greater than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  12794.88      Inf
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  49376.36  33362.50

The sample means and variances were calculated and used to calculate the t statistic as the reference distribution for the hypothesis test is the t-distribution.

We set a confidence level of 95% or in other words a 5% margin. The rejection criteria depends on the significance level (=0.05) for the one-tailed test (testing whether male-dominated majors have higher earnings).

The critical t-value is the threshold value that separates the rejection region from the non-rejection region in the t-distribution. The p-value is the shaded area under the curve beyond the test statistic in the tail of the distribution. The calculated t-value (8.2992) is greater than the critical t-value (1.668) and p-value (3.8e-12) is significantly lower than alpha (0.05). Hence we reject the null hypothesis.

5.1.2 Two-Sample t-Test on Earnings Based on Major Categories (STEM vs.Non-STEM Majors)

The choice of a college major is a significant decision that can impact career prospects, particularly in terms of earnings. STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering, and Mathematics) majors are often believed to have higher earning potential compared to non-STEM majors. To explore whether this perception holds true, a two-sample t-test can be performed to compare the median earnings of graduates from STEM and non-STEM fields. In this dataset all majors from departments Engineering, Physical Sciences, Biology & Life Science, Mathematics & Computer Science and Health are considered as STEM and rest of the departments are Non-STEM majors.

stem_categories <- c("Engineering", "Physical Sciences", "Biology & Life Science", "Mathematics & Computer Science, Health")

# Filter STEM and non-STEM majors
stem_data <- indata %>% filter(Major_category %in% stem_categories)
non_stem_data <- indata %>% filter(!(Major_category %in% stem_categories))

Research Question: Do STEM majors have significantly higher median earnings compared to non-STEM majors?

Null Hypothesis (H0): The mean of median earnings of STEM majors is equal to the mean of median earnings of non-STEM majors.

Alternative Hypothesis (H1): The mean of median earnings of STEM majors is greater than the mean of median earnings of non-STEM majors.

Test Statistic: Since we would be comparing the means of two independent samples (STEM majors vs.non-STEM majors), we use the two-sample t-test.

# Median earnings for STEM and non-STEM majors
stem_medians <- stem_data$Median
non_stem_medians <- non_stem_data$Median

# Sample statistics
mean_stem <- mean(stem_medians, na.rm = TRUE)
mean_stem
## [1] 48922.64
mean_non_stem <- mean(non_stem_medians, na.rm = TRUE)
mean_non_stem
## [1] 36136.97
var_stem <- var(stem_medians, na.rm = TRUE)
var_non_stem <- var(non_stem_medians, na.rm = TRUE)
n_stem <- length(stem_medians)
n_non_stem <- length(non_stem_medians)

# t-statistic calculation
t_statistic <- (mean_stem - mean_non_stem) / sqrt((var_stem / n_stem) + (var_non_stem / n_non_stem))
t_statistic
## [1] 6.142252
df <- ((var_stem / n_stem + var_non_stem / n_non_stem)^2) /
  ((var_stem / n_stem)^2 / (n_stem - 1) + (var_non_stem / n_non_stem)^2 / (n_non_stem - 1))


# Critical t-value for one-tailed test at alpha = 0.05
alpha <- 0.05
t_critical <- qt(1 - alpha, df)
t_critical
## [1] 1.669457
# p-value calculation
p_value <- pt(t_statistic, df, lower.tail = FALSE)
p_value
## [1] 3.057248e-08

The calculated t-statistic is 6.142, which measures how far the sample means are from each other in units of the standard error. This high t-value suggests a significant difference between the group means. The critical t-value is 1.669 for a one-tailed test with a significance level (alpha = 0.05), i.e confidence level of 95%.

The critical value indicates the threshold above which we reject the null hypothesis. As the calculated t-statistic is significantly greater than the critical t-value of 1.669, in addition to the p-value (3.057e-08) being much smaller than the significance level of 0.05, we have strong evidence to reject the null hypothesis.

5.2 Linear Regression

5.2.1 Unemployment Rate vs Median Salary

Understanding the relationship between median salary and unemployment rate can provide valuable insights into the economic outcomes of various majors. This analysis examines whether median salary serves as a significant predictor of unemployment rate using a linear regression approach. By assessing the strength, direction, and statistical significance of this relationship, we aim to determine whether higher median salaries correlate with lower unemployment rates or if other factors might play a more dominant role.

# variables
X_median <- indata$Median
y_unemployment_rate <- indata$Unemployment_rate

(lm.fit <- lm(y_unemployment_rate ~ X_median, data = indata))
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = y_unemployment_rate ~ X_median, data = indata)
## 
## Coefficients:
## (Intercept)     X_median  
##   8.031e-02   -3.065e-07

The above function provides the coefficients for the linear regression model: \(y = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x\)

The estimated intercept is 0.08 which represents the predicted unemployment rate when the median salary is zero. This value is not logically meaningful as median salary wont be going to 0 and graduates would not be interested to work with a salary of 0.

The estimated slope is -3.065e-07, which indicates the change in unemployment rate for a increase in median salary is negligible and as salary goes up, unemployment rate decreases.

The linear regression equation can be represented by Unemployment_rate = 0.08 + -3.065e-07 * Median

# Visualize regression line
ggplot(indata, aes(x = Median, y = Unemployment_rate)) +
  geom_point(color = "blue") + geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red", se = FALSE) +
  labs(title = "Linear Regression on Unemployment Rate vs. Median Salary",
    x = "Median Salary",
    y = "Unemployment Rate") +theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

The plot with the regression line further visualizes the negative, low slope calculated above.

# QQ plot of residuals
fit_residuals <- lm.fit$residuals %>%
  as.data.frame()
fit_residuals %>%
  ggplot(aes(sample = lm.fit$residuals)) + stat_qq(distribution = stats::qnorm) +
  stat_qq_line() + labs( title = "QQ Plot of Residuals",x = "Theoretical Quantiles",y = "Sample Quantiles")+ theme_minimal()

The Quantile-Quantile Plot assess whether the residuals follow a normal distribution, which is an assumption of linear regression. As the residuals deviate significantly from the line (form an S-shape), it indicates a deviation from normality.

# Residuals vs. Index Plot
fit_residuals$Index <- 1:nrow(fit_residuals)
ggplot(fit_residuals, aes(x = Index, y = lm.fit$residuals)) + geom_point(color = "blue") +
  labs(
    title = "Residuals vs. Index",
    x = "Index",
    y = "Residuals"
  ) +theme_minimal()

This plot assess the randomness of residuals over the order of data points. There is some systematic trend or clustering in the plot, however the patters are not significant. This suggests that the residuals are independent and not influenced by the sequence of data points.

ggplot(data = indata, aes(x = X_median, y = residuals(lm.fit))) +
  geom_point(color = "blue", alpha = 0.6) +
  geom_smooth(method = "loess", color = "red", se = FALSE) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 0, linetype = "dashed", color = "black") +
  labs(
    title = "Residuals vs. Median Salary",
    x = "Median Salary",
    y = "Residuals"
  ) +theme_minimal()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

This plot visualizes the residuals (differences between observed and predicted unemployment rates) against the independent variable, Median Salary. The residuals are spread around the horizontal dashed line at y=0. However, there is a slight curved shape in the residuals indicating non-linearity. The red LOESS (Locally Estimated Scatterplot Smoothing) curve shows a slight downward curve at the edges, deviating from zero. This suggests that the model may not fully capture the relationship between median salary and unemployment rate.

confint(lm.fit)
##                     2.5 %       97.5 %

The above function calculates confidence intervals for the coefficients of a linear regression model. In this case, the 95% confidence intervals for the intercept and slope (X_median) are provided.

The residual quartlie values summarize the distribution of residuals.

The t values from the t statistic is also provided above.

Here the null hypothesis (H0) is X_median(slope) = 0 and alternate hypothesis (H1) is X_median is not equals to 0.

The p-value for the slope is 0.13, meaning it is not statistically significant (p > 0.05). With p value of 0.13, we can reject the null hypothesis. Thus, there is insufficient evidence to conclude that the median salary has a meaningful effect on unemployment rate.

Although the residual error is small (0.03022), it doesnt mean a better fit. It must be interpreted relative to the scale of the dependent variable and unemployment rates are all low in the dataset.

The Multiple R-squared value is 0.0134, which means the model explains only 1.34% of the variance in unemployment rate, indicating a very weak relationship. Similarly the low adjusted R score refer to a poor relation.

6. Conclusion

This study examined how different university majors influence employment outcomes, focusing on earnings, job stability, and gender disparities. STEM fields consistently outperformed others with higher median earnings, lower unemployment rates, and fewer graduates in low-wage roles, while non-STEM fields like Arts and Humanities faced more financial challenges and job instability. Gender disparities were evident, with male-dominated majors such as Engineering showing higher earnings and female-dominated fields like Education having lower earnings but higher representation of women.

Hypothesis testing confirmed that male-dominated and STEM majors tend to have significantly higher earnings. However, linear regression revealed a weak and statistically insignificant relationship between median salary and unemployment rate, suggesting that factors beyond salary influence job stability.

This study is limited by its reliance on a single dataset from one university and lack of longitudinal analysis, which restricts insights into long-term career outcomes. Future research could address these gaps by analyzing trends over time, exploring regional job market differences, and investigating the impact of internships and advanced degrees on employment. Additionally, further exploration of gender disparities in specific fields would offer valuable insights to promote equity and workforce diversity.
